{
  "text": "(n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 3; 1.3%), ETEC (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 5; 2.2%), and Salmonella typhi (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 1; 0.44%). Campylobacter and Aeromonas species included C. coli (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 5), C. jejuni (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 2), Campylobacter sp. (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 1), A. caviae (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 1), and A. hydrophila (n \u202b\u05e1\u202c 2). Five strains were biochemically identified as Shigella spp. but did not agglutinate with typing serum. These underwent further analysis; two were PCR positive for the gene encoding invasion plasmid antigen H (ipaH), [CITATION_1] indicating that they might be strains of enteroinvasive E. coli or strains of Shigella not represented by the antiserum panel used, and three were unconfirmed.",
